caption_original:
Happy World Wildlife Day! #FunFact: To protect whales, such as the St. Lawrence beluga and the blue whale, our staff has been studying... their food!

Why? To identify feeding grounds. The findings were then used to inform the shipping industry, who agreed to reduce the speed of vessels in the main feeding grounds in order to reduce the risk of collisions with whales. This is a great example of how Parks Canada is leading by using science to support wildlife protection.

To learn more about this initiative and other Parks Canada species at risk success stories, visit our website: http://www.pc.gc.ca/eng/nature/eep-sar/itm11.aspx.

Got spam?

Avoid opening emails from unknown senders—and if you accidentally do, never reply. Replying confirms your address as being active and causes you to receive more spam. For the same reason, never click on a “remove” or “unsubscribe” link in a suspicious spam message. You may be unwittingly “subscribing” to receiving EVEN MORE spam. 

Check out these 10 tips on how to protect your computer, inbox and mobile device: http://ow.ly/Zm5V3

caption_original:
50th Anniversary of the Great Winnipeg Blizzard 

Winnipeg’s winter of early 1966 was the third coldest year of the century. To make matters worse, on March 4, 1966 a big snow storm piled up 38 cm and was driven by winds gusting up to 112 kilometers per hour. It was the worst winter storm ever recorded for Winnipeg since March 1902 and stranded thousands.

#ScamSpotlight: Be wary of “secret shopper” job opportunities. 

While legit secret shopper jobs do exist, there are lots of fake offers for such desirable gigs. Scammers often contact you via spam email claiming that the job is quick and easy AND pays well.
